adcrumbs for stuffing mix? Any ideas???</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-1056176" class="indented"><a id="comment-1056176"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-281803-1415360830.jpg?itok=HKYHujSC" width="40" height="40" alt="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" title="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">goodfoodteam</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 21st May, 2018</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Thanks for your question. Stuffing mix tends to have additional flavours like onion and sage which will affect the overall outcome of the pie. The breadcrumbs here are purely for binding purposes.</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-895011"><a id="comment-895011"></a><article class="comment"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"> <span class="comment__author-picture--no-login"></span></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">ClaraClayton</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 23rd Dec, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Hello, I made this fab pie last night. I fully baked it (after cooking at 190 for and hour and 180 for 25mins) I then froze it.
I want to use the pie for New Years Day. Next week can I defrost it in the fridge for say 24hrs and then eat it cold without rebaking the pie? I looked at the questions just now and realised maybe I should have frozen it before I baked it. I don't want to waste the pie and throw it away but I think it will be dry and burnt if I bake it again. Grateful for any advice thankyou x</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-894191"><a id="comment-894191"></a><article class="comment"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-611657-1389982231.jpg?itok=aHBAchX8" width="40" height="40" alt="pennyclark&#039;s picture" title="pennyclark&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">pennyclark</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 19th Dec, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">I made this tonight but it had a soggy bottom and the filling shrunk away from the sides, was this anything to do with me missing out the breadcrumbs? If not any advise would be appreciated:)</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-894731" class="indented"><a id="comment-894731"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-281803-1415360830.jpg?itok=HKYHujSC" width="40" height="40" alt="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" title="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">goodfoodteam</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 22nd Dec, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Yes the breadcrumbs are there for a couple of reasons. They absorb meat juices from the sausage and chicken, which stops the mixture becoming too wet and they also stop shrinkage.&nbsp;</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-894061"><a id="comment-894061"></a><article class="comment"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"> <span class="comment__author-picture--no-login"></span></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">karenxross</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 19th Dec, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Hi, I wonder if you could suggest an alternative to sausage meat for this pie?</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-894736" class="indented"><a id="comment-894736"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-281803-1415360830.jpg?itok=HKYHujSC" width="40" height="40" alt="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" title="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">goodfoodteam</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 22nd Dec, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">The sausage meat is the glue that helps everything to stick together so you will need to create something similar. We haven&rsquo;t tried it ourselves, but 400g minced pork or chicken with 200g breadcrumbs and a beaten egg should do the trick, but the end result might have a slightly firmer texture. You will need to increase the seasonings and herbs a little too.</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-892446"><a id="comment-892446"></a><article class="comment"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"> <span class="comment__author-picture--no-login"></span></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">sandrar57</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 13th Dec, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">If I cooked this on Dec 23rd would it keep in the fridge until Boxing Day?</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-893716" class="indented"><a id="comment-893716"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-281803-1415360830.jpg?itok=HKYHujSC" width="40" height="40" alt="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" title="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">goodfoodteam</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 18th Dec, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Yes it is fine to keep this in the fridge for a few days.</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><di